  "text": "on the y-axis. The cause group implies the meaning of an influencing criterion, with the influence used to estimate the weights of the criteria. Factors from the cause group have a higher priority and higher intensity in relation to the effect criteria. Effect criteria receive more influence and therefore have lower priority [CITATION_1] . From a change perspective the cause criteria are more readily adapted as direct input change will lead to direct output change. The effect criteria are more difficult to influence directly and identified change activities may not result in predicted better performance. This is due to the natural influence of the cause criteria on the effect criteria. Effect criteria are by their nature directly influenced by the many cause criteria and thus less predictable in change efforts. Thus change efforts from a practice perspective are best spent on cause criteria, which if carried out correctly should also positively impact upon effect criteria. In the criteria causal diagram, the retailer selection evaluation factors are visually divided into the cause group which includes C 1 (management abilities and skills), C 3 (flexible organisation), C 5 (workforce skills and training), C 12 (customer service orientation and capability), C 13 (product compatibility), C 16 (willingness to share information), C 19 (manufacturer's familiarity with the retailer), C 21 (on-time deliveries), C 22 (information security system), C 23 (strong IT infrastructure) and C 24 (technology compatibility). The effect group is composed of C 2 (high internal alignment), C 4 (organisational size), C 6 (financial strength), C 7 (physical facilities), C 8 (reputation), C 9 (sales strength), C 10 (market coverage), C 11 (familiarity with the product), C 14 (footfall), C 15 (retailers commitment to agreed order), C 17 (retailers' initiative to build trust), C 18 (enthusiasm to collaboration) and C 20 (inventory management). Generally, the factors in the effect group tend to be easily impacted by others, which makes effect factors unsuitable to be a critical success factor in a partner selection process. The findings of Figure Step 7: Set the threshold value and obtain the impact relation map",
